text: As a diehard X-Men fan my whole life, this doesn't look bad but I'm still worried. 20th Century Fox has completely complicated the X-Men movie universe. There are so many questions left hanging after X-Men 3, First Class, the Wolverine movies and etc. If they just brush over all those in your face facts (i.e. how is Xavier's body fully in tact after being utterly obliterated in X-Men 3? How is McAvoy walking after the events of first class? In the X-Men 3 intro flashback Patrick Stewart as Xavier was walking as his older self. How is that possible? There were sentinels in the X-Men 3 danger room but now they finally just show up now?) These are just a small handful but big glaring potholes Bryan Singer and Fox have to deal with. To be honest I'd rather this movie just bomb so Marvel and Disney get the X-Men rights and they just reboot the entire franchise from scratch and with new actors.

text: I'll always wonder what the original X-Men trilogy could have been had Singer never abandoned X-Men for Superman Returns. Not only the trilogy but the Wolverine origins movie which wasn't much better would have both been completely different and likely significantly better if Singer been involved in any way or had the directors of X-Men: The Last Stand or X-Men Origins:Wolverine had any business directing X-men movies. The last 2 X-men films (First Class & The Wolverine) didn't have Singer involved and were both good films that were much more true to their roots but that's probably because like Singer, Matthew Vaughn & James Mangold are both proven quality directors who have probably actually read some x-men comics where as Brent Ratner and Gavin Hood had no business directing their respective X-men films and neither was known at the times they were asked to direct their movies for directing quality action films. Just because the Rush Hour movies were pretty funny doesn't make them good movies. It's just nice to see that Fox got their heads out of their asses over the last few years and has gotten the franchise back on track. It's going to be so fun to see where film technology takes both the X-Men & Avengers franchises over the next decade. I remember when they made X-Men United they could only have Colossus in his mutant form for like a minute of screen time because it was insanely expensive for his CGI, how things have changed in just 11 years.

text: First of all, Bishop and Cable arent in DOFP. ITs Bishop going into the past to prevent the assassination of Senator Kelly. Wolverine does not go back in time cos he was to old to recover from time traveling. Later they all figured out that Mystique disguised as Gambit and attempted to kill the senator.    At some point Apocalypse, Cable, and Bishop are in a series too. Its Cable going back in time to prevent what Bishop did cos it changed Cables future.  Lastly, no matter how many attempts these mutants do the future still stays the same. I hate how the films change the storylines, however, I still enjoy the films.   Look up these episodes from the Xmen animated series where they based they're storylines on the Marvel Comics: Days of Future Past, Time Fugitives, One Man's Worth, Beyond Good and Evil.

text: Can you all just hear me out for a quick sec? I'm not even trying to sound like a beggar here but to those of you who are questioning on seeing this film PLEASE don't let the foolishness of some of these comments convince you all to pass on supporting what looks/happens to be one of the biggest emotional, action packed and character driven comic book movie we've had since 2012's Avengers movie. I just wish people would stop the war zone comment section of which film is better when it comes to Marvel/Disney and Fox movies. BOTH studios have had crappy films in the past and BOTH studios are working towards becoming better within the "quality" of their films rather than the quantity. Captain America: The Winter Soldier is getting great reviews and for Marvel finally giving us a pretty serious and thrilling action flick I applaud them on their tremendous job on handling the story and characters rather than using their well known humor (as many fans have stated) that can sometimes take away from their films. X-Men: Days of Future Past deserves this chance people! Even though DOFP is my most anticipated CBM of the summer I'm going to still support other comic book movies because this IS the year we deserve for CBMs. All I ask is that you just give this film a chance. If any director earns another shot at the X-Men it's the original and first director Bryan Singer! I believe in Bryan Singer. So with that being said...LET'S GET IT X-MEN!!!!!!!!!! :,)

text: 2014 has a lot of mind grabbing movies. Five movies that peaked my interest and I really want to see them in theaters. Interestingly, most of them are sequels. First is The Amazing Spiderman 2, since I've been to every Spider man movie at the theaters it kind of became my tradition to watch them on their day of release. Second is How to Train Your Dragon 2, loved the original, let's see how the sequel does.  Third is Guardians of the Galaxy, a different approach on Marvel's side. I want to see how it does, and I'm a sucker for space adventures. Fourth is Transformers 4. I am giving Michael Bay one more chance. And then that's it. And this... the only other X men movie that I am interested in besides First Class. Although I do praise Ian McKellen's acting. He's a wonderful actor.

text: I think it looks awesome. I'll be honest, I only read a few comics so long ago that I don't even remember what they were about. I've seen all the movies. And although the last movie had some really cheesy and flat out horrible parts in it, I thoroughly enjoyed how it showed the roots of Magneto and Xavier's conflict. The action was meh, but the focus on the contrasting beliefs between the two men was brilliant IMO. Magneto was always portrayed as this sort of tyrannic, mad man in the previous movies, but when you saw his upbringing, it was hard to blame him for wanting to defend his own kind, knowing that society would not accept them. Not to mention Fassbender version of Magneto is badass. I have a feeling this film will combine the action of the previous first 3 movies and the clash of opinions/perspectives (especially with future versions of the X-Men), being performed by a lot of really great actors.

text: As awesome as this looks, I'm sorta getting tired of Wolverine being the protagonist in ALL OF THE DAMN FILMS! I understand Fox does this so they don't shit in their pants out of worry that they'll have to give up the rights to X-Men, but they really need to take more liberties and think out of the box. There are PLENTY of other potential main protagonists that Fox could use in their X-Men movies, but they think the mainstream audience won't go to see them because, OMG WOLVERINE ISN'T IN IT!!! It's actually not that true and I've seen many of these "mainstream" audience members start to complain and downright hate on the X-Men film franchise since Wolverine is the main hero in ALL of them. Look, Hugh Jackman is a great actor and he was certainly born for the role but overusing him will end up in the X-Men film franchise's downfall. Plus, even if Fox grows some balls and finally  makes a X-Men movie without Wolverine, and it fails, they always have Deadpool to lean on. Seriously, fans have been creating petitions and yelling their asses off to get production going... WHERE THE FUCK IS DEADPOOL?! HUH?! WHERE THE FUCK IS HE?!

text: You don't know X-Men until you seen this story. I remember reading this back in High School not able to put the comic down for a second cause it was so dark full of despair and emotion that what X-Men stood for and bringing their worse fears to life.  I don't mind the redesign of the Sentinels as much as I love the motionless roman golem look they had in the comics with far out coloring pallet it worked for comics cause it gave a still impression of fear. As a live action movie bringing the destructive intensity of the energy blast is the main point of their position in the story as those who read know what I mean about this.  Two great cast clashing in the most epic story that touched my creative imagination back then finally comes to pass in this feudal and emotional story line. Thank you Marvel and Hollywood and Bryan Singer for doing this. I hope we see more of swarms of Sentinels flying in the night sky like we saw here cause that was perfect image of the mood and destruction the comic had.

text: HERE'S MY ANALYSIS OF THE TRAILER   people keep saying that the timeline don't make sense because in trailer wolverine is old but Xavier and Magneato look same as in credits to wolverine..u ever think only wolverine has aged..think about it...everyone in the trailer looks pretty much the same age as from X-MEN the Last Stand,Bobby,Kitty,Storm,Rogue,Magneato,Xavier etc etc...maybe only Wolverine has aged do to countless encounters with the sentinels..because its his healing factor that plays a vital role in him not aging..so countless battles has probably exhausted his healing abilities and he has finally began aging and it why out of everyone shown in future clips he was the only one aged..makes complete sense if u had to think about it...he is the badass un-killable mutant that loves whooping evil asses...sentinels would be on his ass non stop so he would have gotten fucked up 6-8 times a day..that would have weakened his healing ability so he might start aging rapidly with every battle.,...that's my theory..i mean he is supposed to be the main protagonist of the newest film right?makes sense they try and show the war has effected him and his amazing abilities..and that even the future has made him weak and that it must be changed.  and as for Xavier talking to himself..he obviously implanted messages in Logan's mind for himself..that face to face is more theatrics...obviously he was looking into Logan's mind and seeing his older self talking to Logan when he was implanting the message  and as for erasing the future with this whole story..like UN-doing all movies 1 through 3...in the comics version of days of future past all there plan to undo the future did was create a alternate timeline the older timeline went unchanged...so who knows what direction they will go in  some people who watch comic movies have never truly read comic books, so them picking out stupid stuff in trailers is laughable because they know not very much about the heroes they cheer...but those who have read comics don't post ur complaints on the trailers,..ur smarter than that to know anything u see in a trailer makes u wanna speculate and get u thinking because the comic fans out there have wanted to see this movies happen for years..ur smarter so at least wait for the movies release to complain, at least then u can confirm if what ur bitching about is real or just speculation based on small snippets of a 2 minute trailer

text: So excited for this movie.  Bryan Singer is taking a HUGE risk with Days of Future Past, which is exciting.  A lot of film directors like to play it safe in hopes that they don't do something stupid that might jeopardize their career.  As a result, they end up with "safe" movies, that aren't bad, but aren't great.  Days of Future Past could fail, or it could succeed, but either way, Singer's going big.  Gotta respect that!  For the record, I think it's going to kick ass and I can't wait to see what Singer has in store for us with Apocalyspe.

text: For those of you who keep saying "X-Men 3 is no longer canon" or that it's being "written out of existence", why do you keep saying that? If you actually SAW X-Men 3, you'd see that Magneto didn't lose ALL of his powers and that Xavier managed to find another body, hence why they are both appearing in this movie.  Now as for Magneto getting back to full strength and Xavier finding a clone body, well that needs more explaining.  And if you saw The Wolverine, which takes place AFTER X-Men 3, it not only acknowledges X3 through several references and a subtplot with Logan feeling bad about killing Jean by stabbing her, but it also clearly ties it in to Days of Future Past.  In the post credits of The Wolverine, Logan was clearly shocked to see Xavier alive (though admittedly not that shocked that Magneto had powers), so again, X-Men 3 is canon, ALL the movies are canon and there's no movie being left out. That said, that doesn't make things that much better since X-Men: First Class ruined the timeline by not only contradicting X-Men 3, but ALL of the previous X-Men movies.  I don't know how Days of Future Past is gonna fix that, but it had better, otherwise this whole film series makes no sense anymore.

text: I will certainly go see this one, since I like the cast, but I don't understand why the producers are A) showing us the whole movie in the trailer: hate it when they do that. And B) producing what (to me) seems like a finale in a long, long series of movies. As in, what happened, Magneto and Professor X had just about fallen out and started opposing each other, and all of a sudden we get the "back from the future to save them all" story? text: In my Overrall opinion on the change of kitty pryde to wolverine was completely sexist and embarrassing. Why I say embarrassing is beacsue there excuse so totally immature! Saying Oh "Wolverine is the most beloved character" is basically in my opinion another way of suger-coding saying that it should be a male role model with More experience. Why make a movie about the xmen original story if basically the whole entire movie is going to be changed? as a kitty pryde fan I was completely furious when I heard about this sudden change, and then it caused me to hate the wolverine character more then I had already did so. I agree with other peoples opinions saying that they over use wolverine as the main character in every movie. in My honest opinion I don't know why people like wolverine that much anyway! hes basically a male version of a badass cat. When I say they focus on him to much is like for example...- the story between phoenix "jean grey' and scott summers was one of the most important more cared about scenario in the xmen franchise and yet there hasn't been a movie about them, instead they put out a movie such as wolverine origens which really wasn't all that important and cared for. Back on the main topic, they could've made some adjustments that could still allow ellen page or kitty pryde to still be the leading character such as drag the time line earlier or something so she could actually be alive (if they could make a drastic move like replacing her completely the they could've done something like this) but instead on actually giving her a chance in the movie they completely replaced her. And anyone saying that main characters have to be well known are lying. If you look at first class Mystique, Banshee, pixie, havoc etc. weren't really known characters but they got to play a major role in the film portrayed as main characters. I just think this decision was utterly immature and stupid.

text: the movie turns 6 today! still one of the franchises best seeing these two generations of characters collide along with the actors makes it that much more surreal plus they make the whole time travel gimmick work Singer manages to juggle multiple mutants while still keeping to the central core of the comics with its symbolic prejudice themes and making it emotional  I know a lot of fans hated what Ratner and Hood did to the series and this movie erases all of those issues but I enjoy every one of these movies I skipped Dark Phoenix like the plague, ended on such a sour note which is a shame cause I freaking love X-Men hopefully with the Disney/Fox merger now they can rectify this and finally bring these characters in a whole new light into the MCU
